WEBVTT

00:23.940 --> 00:26.740
CHAPTER XVIII.

00:26.740 --> 00:31.040
Day after day, week after week, passed away on my return to Geneva,

00:32.300 --> 00:35.120
and I could not collect the courage to recommence my work.

00:36.280 --> 00:39.200
I feared the vengeance of the disappointed fiend,

00:39.660 --> 00:44.380
yet I was unable to overcome my repugnance to the task which was enjoined me.

00:45.260 --> 00:47.740
I found that I could not compose a female,

00:48.500 --> 00:53.100
without again devoting several months to profound study and laborious disquisition.

00:53.700 --> 00:57.900
I had heard of some discoveries having been made by an English philosopher,

00:58.800 --> 01:01.240
the knowledge of which was material to my success,

01:02.100 --> 01:06.520
and I sometimes thought of obtaining my father's consent to visit England for this purpose,

01:07.360 --> 01:12.680
but I clung to every pretense of delay and shrank from taking the first step in an undertaking

01:12.680 --> 01:16.260
whose immediate necessity began to appear less absolute to me.

01:17.260 --> 01:19.420
A change indeed had taken place in me.

01:19.420 --> 01:23.980
My health, which had hitherto declined, was now much restored,

01:24.620 --> 01:31.420
and my spirits, when unchecked by the memory of my unhappy promise, rose proportionably.

01:32.720 --> 01:34.560
My father saw this change with pleasure,

01:34.920 --> 01:39.320
and he turned his thoughts towards the best method of eradicating the remains of my melancholy,

01:40.240 --> 01:42.800
which every now and then would return by fits,

01:43.660 --> 01:48.140
and with a devouring blackness overcast the approaching sunshine.

01:48.960 --> 01:53.360
At these moments I took refuge in the most perfect solitude.

01:54.940 --> 01:57.980
I passed whole days on the lake alone in a little boat,

01:58.740 --> 02:05.080
watching the clouds and listening to the rippling of the waves, silent and listless.

02:06.980 --> 02:11.100
But the fresh air and bright sun seldom failed to restore me to some degree of composure,

02:11.300 --> 02:17.500
and on my return I met the salutations of my friends with a readier smile and a more cheerful heart.

02:17.500 --> 02:23.560
It was after my return from one of these rambles that my father, calling me aside, thus addressed me.

02:23.940 --> 02:30.280
I am happy to remark, my dear son, that you have resumed your former pleasures and seem to be returning to yourself.

02:31.160 --> 02:35.100
And yet you are still unhappy and still avoid our society.

02:36.020 --> 02:39.300
For some time I was lost in conjecture as to the cause of this,

02:39.800 --> 02:45.860
but yesterday an idea struck me, and if it is well founded I conjure you to avow it.

02:45.860 --> 02:52.980
Reserve on such a point would be not only useless, but draw down treble misery on us all.

02:54.060 --> 02:58.720
I trembled violently at his exhortium, and my father continued,

02:59.760 --> 03:04.640
I confess, my son, that I have always looked forward to your marriage with our dear Elizabeth

03:04.640 --> 03:09.840
as the tie of our domestic comfort and the stay of my declining years.

03:10.340 --> 03:15.060
You were attached to each other from your earliest infancy, you studied together,

03:15.060 --> 03:19.620
and appeared in dispositions and tastes entirely suited to one another.

03:20.440 --> 03:29.600
But so blind is the experience of man that what I conceive to be the best assistance to my plan may have entirely destroyed it.

03:29.860 --> 03:35.880
You, perhaps, regarded her as your sister, without any wish that she might become your wife.

03:36.520 --> 03:42.440
Nay, you may have met with another whom you may love, and considering yourself as bound in honor to Elizabeth,

03:42.440 --> 03:47.300
this struggle may occasion the poignant misery which you appear to feel.

03:48.300 --> 03:53.540
My dear father, reassure yourself, I love my cousin tenderly and sincerely.

03:54.120 --> 04:00.440
I never saw any woman who excited, as Elizabeth does, my warmest admiration and affection.

04:01.120 --> 04:05.540
My future hopes and prospects are entirely bound up in the expectation of our union.

04:06.660 --> 04:14.100
The expression of your sentiments on this subject, my dear Victor, gives me more pleasure than I have for some time experienced.

04:14.480 --> 04:17.720
If you feel thus, we shall assuredly be happy.

04:18.180 --> 04:21.100
However, present events may cast a gloom over us.

04:21.840 --> 04:27.880
But it is this gloom which appears to have taken so strong a hold of your mind that I wish to dissipate.

04:28.520 --> 04:33.340
Tell me, therefore, whether you object to an immediate solemnization of the marriage.

04:33.340 --> 04:42.600
We have been unfortunate, and recent events have drawn us from that everyday tranquility befitting my years and infirmities.

04:43.260 --> 04:48.440
You are younger, yet I do not suppose, possessed as you are of a competent fortune,

04:48.800 --> 04:55.600
that an early marriage would at all interfere with any future plans of honor and utility that you may have formed.

04:56.310 --> 05:00.600
Do not suppose, however, that I wish to dictate happiness to you,

05:00.600 --> 05:04.640
or that a delay on your part would cause me any serious uneasiness.

05:05.560 --> 05:11.620
Interpret my words with candor, and answer me, I conjure you, with confidence and sincerity.

05:12.720 --> 05:18.760
I listen to my father in silence, and remain for some time incapable of offering any reply.

05:19.460 --> 05:25.440
I revolved rapidly in my mind a multitude of thoughts, and endeavored to arrive at some conclusion.

05:26.300 --> 05:32.960
Alas, to me the idea of an immediate union with my Elizabeth was one of horror and dismay.

05:33.660 --> 05:40.300
I was bound by a solemn promise which I had not yet fulfilled, and dared not break.

05:40.780 --> 05:46.800
Or if I did, what manifold miseries might not impend over me and my devoted family?

05:47.580 --> 05:55.760
Could I enter into a festival with this deadly weight yet hanging round my neck and bowing me to the ground?

05:56.500 --> 06:01.380
I must perform my engagement, and let the monster depart with his mate,

06:02.140 --> 06:06.860
before I allowed myself to enjoy the delight of a union from which I expected peace.

06:07.520 --> 06:11.840
I remembered also the necessity imposed upon me of either journeying to England,

06:11.840 --> 06:15.860
or entering into a long correspondence with those philosophers of that country

06:15.860 --> 06:20.280
whose knowledge and discoveries were of indispensable use to me in my present undertaking.

06:21.880 --> 06:26.720
The latter method of obtaining the desired intelligence was dilatory and unsatisfactory.

06:27.880 --> 06:34.900
Besides, I had an insurmountable aversion to the idea of engaging myself in my loathsome task in my father's house,

06:35.780 --> 06:38.660
while in habits of familiar intercourse with those I loved.

06:39.620 --> 06:43.460
I knew that a thousand fearful accidents might occur,

06:44.080 --> 06:50.140
the slightest of which would disclose a tale to thrill all connected with me with horror.

06:51.280 --> 06:55.480
I was aware also that I should often lose all self-command,

06:56.180 --> 07:02.240
all capacity of hiding the harrowing sensations that would possess me during the progress of my unearthly occupation.

07:02.640 --> 07:07.420
I must absent myself from all I loved while thus employed.

07:08.660 --> 07:15.060
Once commenced, it would quickly be achieved, and I might be restored to my family in peace and happiness.

07:16.360 --> 07:20.620
My promise fulfilled, the monster would depart forever.

07:21.900 --> 07:28.280
Or, so my fond fancy imaged, some accident might meanwhile occur to destroy him,

07:29.000 --> 07:31.300
and put an end to my slavery forever.

07:32.580 --> 07:35.020
These feelings dictated my answer to my father.

07:35.020 --> 07:40.740
I expressed a wish to visit England, but concealing the true reasons of this request,

07:41.080 --> 07:45.180
I clothed my desires under a guise which excited no suspicion,

07:45.880 --> 07:50.980
while I urged my desire with an earnestness that easily induced my father to comply.

07:53.040 --> 07:58.760
After so long a period of an absorbing melancholy that resembled madness in its intensity and effects,

07:59.380 --> 08:03.280
he was glad to find that I was capable of taking pleasure in the idea of such a journey,

08:03.280 --> 08:11.680
and he hoped that change of scene and varied amusement would, before my return, have restored me entirely to myself.

08:12.960 --> 08:15.540
The duration of my absence was left to my own choice.

08:15.880 --> 08:19.800
A few months, or at most a year, was the period contemplated.

08:20.520 --> 08:25.040
One paternal kind precaution he had taken to ensure my having a companion.

08:26.180 --> 08:31.500
Without previously communicating with me, he had, in concert with Elizabeth,

08:31.500 --> 08:35.640
arranged that Clare Valle should join me at Strasbourg.

08:36.640 --> 08:40.620
This interfered with the solitude I coveted for the prosecution of my task.

08:41.720 --> 08:46.340
Yet at the commencement of my journey the presence of my friend could in no way be an impediment,

08:46.880 --> 08:52.460
and truly I rejoiced that thus I should be saved many hours of lonely, maddening reflection.

08:53.240 --> 08:57.500
Nay, Henry might stand between me and the intrusion of my foe.

08:57.500 --> 09:05.360
If I were alone, would he not at times force his abhorred presence on me to remind me of my task,

09:05.880 --> 09:07.560
or to contemplate its progress?

09:08.580 --> 09:10.480
To England, therefore, I was bound,

09:10.880 --> 09:15.340
and it was understood that my union with Elizabeth should take place immediately on my return.

09:16.180 --> 09:19.000
My father's age rendered him extremely averse to delay.

09:20.300 --> 09:25.000
For myself there was one reward I promised myself from my detested toils,

09:25.000 --> 09:29.540
one consolation for my unparalleled sufferings.

09:30.520 --> 09:36.620
It was the prospect of that day when, enfranchised from my miserable slavery,

09:37.360 --> 09:42.480
I might claim Elizabeth and forget the past in my union with her.

09:43.700 --> 09:45.560
I now made arrangements for my journey,

09:45.780 --> 09:50.600
but one feeling haunted me which filled me with fear and agitation.

09:51.580 --> 09:56.360
During my absence I should leave my friends unconscious of the existence of their enemy

09:56.360 --> 10:02.660
and unprotected from his attacks, exacerbated as he might be by my departure.

10:04.140 --> 10:08.940
But he had promised to follow me wherever I might go, and would he not accompany me to England?

10:10.100 --> 10:16.460
This imagination was dreadful in itself, but soothing inasmuch as it supposed the safety of my friends.

10:17.540 --> 10:23.020
I was agonized with the idea of the possibility that the reverse of this might happen.

10:24.160 --> 10:27.900
But through the whole period during which I was the slave of my creature,

10:28.460 --> 10:31.540
I allowed myself to be governed by the impulses of the moment,

10:32.420 --> 10:37.160
and my present sensation strongly intimated that the fiend would follow me

10:37.160 --> 10:40.460
and exempt my family from the danger of his machinations.

10:41.640 --> 10:46.220
It was in the latter end of September that I again quitted my native country.

10:47.020 --> 10:51.140
My journey had been my own suggestion, and Elizabeth therefore acquiesced.

10:51.580 --> 10:55.580
But she was filled with disquiet at the idea of my suffering away from her,

10:55.840 --> 10:57.820
the inroads of misery and grief.

10:58.560 --> 11:01.980
It had been her care which provided me a companion in Clareval,

11:02.860 --> 11:05.760
and yet a man is blind to a thousand minute circumstances

11:05.760 --> 11:08.740
which call forth a woman's sedulous attention.

11:09.400 --> 11:12.040
She longed to bid me haste in my return.

11:12.880 --> 11:18.440
A thousand conflicting emotions rendered her mute as she bade me a tearful, silent farewell.

11:19.480 --> 11:22.820
I threw myself into the carriage that was to convey me away,

11:23.720 --> 11:28.080
hardly knowing whither I was going, and careless of what was passing around.

11:28.820 --> 11:32.840
I remembered only, and it was with a bitter anguish that I reflected on it,

11:33.200 --> 11:36.830
to order that my chemical instruments should be packed to go with me.

11:37.790 --> 11:43.130
Filled with dreary imaginations, I passed through many beautiful and majestic scenes,

11:43.870 --> 11:46.010
but my eyes were fixed and unobserving.

11:46.950 --> 11:49.090
I could only think of the bourne of my travels,

11:49.550 --> 11:52.450
and the work which was to occupy me whilst they endured.

11:53.810 --> 11:58.650
After some days spent in listless indolence, during which I traversed many leagues,

11:59.210 --> 12:02.970
I arrived at Strasbourg, where I waited two days for Clareval.

12:03.570 --> 12:04.470
He came.

12:05.530 --> 12:08.290
Lass, how great was the contrast between us!

12:08.730 --> 12:14.030
He was alive to every new scene, joyful when he saw the beauties of the setting sun,

12:14.670 --> 12:18.010
and more happy when he beheld it rise and recommence a new day.

12:18.790 --> 12:23.090
He pointed out to me the shifting colours of the landscape and the appearances of the sky.

12:23.990 --> 12:29.170
This is what it is to live, he cried. How I enjoy existence!

12:29.170 --> 12:34.610
But you, my dear Frankenstein, wherefore are you desponding and sorrowful?

12:35.950 --> 12:38.710
In truth, I was occupied by gloomy thoughts,

12:39.090 --> 12:44.170
and neither saw the descent of the evening star nor the golden sunrise reflected in the Rhine.

12:45.210 --> 12:49.770
And you, my friend, would be far more amused with the journal of Clareval,

12:50.290 --> 12:53.250
who observed the scenery with an eye of feeling and delight,

12:53.930 --> 12:55.550
than in listening to my reflections.

12:56.330 --> 13:02.770
Ay, a miserable wretch, haunted by a curse that shut up every avenue to enjoyment.

13:04.550 --> 13:08.690
We had agreed to descend the Rhine in a boat from Strasbourg to Rotterdam,

13:10.010 --> 13:11.890
whence we might take shipping for London.

13:13.050 --> 13:18.130
During this voyage we passed many willowy islands and saw several beautiful towns.

13:18.770 --> 13:23.310
We stayed a day at Mannheim, and on the fifth from our departure from Strasbourg,

13:23.310 --> 13:24.850
arrived at Mains.

13:26.070 --> 13:30.330
The course of the Rhine below Mains becomes much more picturesque.

13:30.790 --> 13:37.310
The river descends rapidly and winds between hills, not high but steep, and of beautiful forms.

13:38.270 --> 13:42.110
We saw many ruined castles standing on the edges of precipices,

13:42.710 --> 13:46.170
surrounded by black woods, high and inaccessible.

13:47.270 --> 13:52.070
This part of the Rhine, indeed, presents a singularly variegated landscape.

13:52.070 --> 13:58.570
In one spot you view rugged hills, ruined castles overlooking tremendous precipices,

13:58.970 --> 14:01.150
with a dark Rhine rushing beneath.

14:01.890 --> 14:06.230
And on the sudden turn of a promontory, flourishing vineyards,

14:06.710 --> 14:11.530
with green sloping banks and a meandering river and populous towns occupy the scene.

14:12.990 --> 14:15.230
We travelled at the time of the vintage,

14:15.750 --> 14:19.090
and heard the song of the labourers as we glided down the stream.

14:19.090 --> 14:24.750
Even I, depressed in mind and my spirits continually agitated by gloomy feelings,

14:25.270 --> 14:26.570
even I was pleased.

14:27.490 --> 14:32.570
I lay at the bottom of the boat, and as I gazed on the cloudless blue sky,

14:33.410 --> 14:36.910
I seemed to drink in a tranquillity to which I had long been a stranger.

14:38.230 --> 14:41.450
And if these were my sensations, who could describe those of Henry?

14:41.450 --> 14:45.190
He felt as if he had been transported to Fairyland,

14:45.650 --> 14:48.130
and enjoyed a happiness seldom tasted by man.

14:48.810 --> 14:54.270
I have seen, he said, the most beautiful scenes of my own country.

14:54.650 --> 14:57.410
I have visited the lakes of Lucerne and Uri,

14:57.730 --> 15:01.870
where the snowy mountains descend almost perpendicularly to the water,

15:02.070 --> 15:04.490
casting black and impenetrable shades,

15:04.810 --> 15:09.330
which would cause a gloomy and mournful appearance were it not for the most verdant islands

15:09.330 --> 15:12.150
that believe the eye by their gay appearance.

15:13.290 --> 15:16.450
I have seen this lake agitated by a tempest,

15:16.630 --> 15:20.190
when the wind tore up whirlwinds of water and gave you an idea

15:20.190 --> 15:22.710
of what the waterspout must be on the great ocean,

15:23.190 --> 15:26.290
and the waves dash with fury the base of the mountain,

15:26.770 --> 15:30.230
where the priest and his mistress were overwhelmed by an avalanche,

15:30.270 --> 15:34.730
and where their dying voices are still said to be heard amid the pauses of the nightly wind.

15:35.670 --> 15:40.850
I have seen the mountains of La Vallée and the Pays-du-Vaux,

15:41.410 --> 15:46.370
but this country, Victor, pleases me more than all those wonders.

15:47.190 --> 15:50.490
The mountains of Switzerland are more majestic and strange,

15:51.230 --> 15:57.850
but there is a charm in the banks of this divine river that I never before saw equalled.

15:58.210 --> 16:01.350
Look at that castle which overhangs yon precipice,

16:01.350 --> 16:07.970
and that also on the island, almost concealed among the foliage of those beautiful trees,

16:08.850 --> 16:13.350
and now that group of laborers coming from among their vines,

16:13.670 --> 16:16.310
and that village half-hid in the recess of the mountain.

16:17.430 --> 16:23.830
Oh, surely the spirit that inhabits and guards this place has a soul more in harmony with man

16:23.830 --> 16:30.790
than those who pile the glacier or retire to the inaccessible peaks of the mountains of our own country.

16:32.370 --> 16:38.650
Clairvaux, beloved friend, even now it delights me to record your words

16:38.650 --> 16:42.410
and to dwell on the praise of which you are so eminently deserving.

16:43.330 --> 16:47.270
He was a being formed in the very poetry of nature.

16:47.950 --> 16:52.710
His wild and enthusiastic imagination was chastened by the sensibility of his heart.

16:53.530 --> 16:56.690
His soul overflowed with ardent affections,

16:56.690 --> 17:00.230
and his friendship was of that devoted and wondrous nature

17:00.230 --> 17:03.910
that the world-minded teach us to look for only in the imagination.

17:05.230 --> 17:08.870
But even human sympathies were not sufficient to satisfy his eager mind.

17:10.070 --> 17:17.110
The scenery of external nature, which others regard only with admiration, he loved with ardor.

17:17.930 --> 17:21.370
The sounding cataract haunted him like a passion.

17:21.370 --> 17:25.430
The tall rock, the mountain, and the deep gloomy wood,

17:25.690 --> 17:29.290
their colors and their forms were then to him an appetite,

17:29.950 --> 17:36.070
a feeling, and a love that had no need of a remoter charm by thought supplied

17:36.070 --> 17:39.250
or any interest unborrowed from the eye.

17:44.160 --> 17:46.270
And where does he now exist?

17:47.450 --> 17:49.950
Is this gentle and lovely being lost forever?

17:50.730 --> 17:55.670
Has this mind, so replete with ideas, imaginations, fanciful and magnificent,

17:56.270 --> 18:00.650
which formed a world whose existence depended on the life of its creator,

18:01.870 --> 18:03.450
has this mind perished?

18:04.250 --> 18:06.470
Does it now only exist in my memory?

18:07.450 --> 18:10.250
No, it is not thus.

18:11.010 --> 18:17.210
Your form, so divinely wrought and beaming with beauty, has decayed.

18:17.210 --> 18:23.250
But your spirit still visits and consoles your unhappy friend.

18:24.770 --> 18:26.390
Pardon this gush of sorrow.

18:27.710 --> 18:33.210
These ineffectual words are but a slight tribute to the unexampled worth of Henry.

18:34.330 --> 18:39.930
But they soothe my heart, overflowing with the anguish which his remembrance creates.

18:42.310 --> 18:43.950
I will proceed with my tale.

18:45.510 --> 18:48.210
Beyond Cologne we descended to the plains of Holland,

18:49.090 --> 18:51.730
and we resolved to post the remainder of our way,

18:52.010 --> 18:57.170
for the wind was contrary and the stream of the river was too gentle to aid us.

18:58.390 --> 19:01.830
Our journey here lost the interest arising from beautiful scenery,

19:02.370 --> 19:06.950
but we arrived in a few days at Rotterdam, whence we proceeded by sea to England.

19:07.730 --> 19:10.890
It was on a clear morning in the latter days of December

19:10.890 --> 19:13.850
that I first saw the white cliffs of Britain.

19:15.250 --> 19:17.810
The banks of the Thames presented a new scene.

19:18.910 --> 19:20.530
They were flat, but fertile,

19:21.030 --> 19:24.570
and almost every town was marked by the remembrance of some story.

19:25.550 --> 19:29.230
We saw Tilbury Fort and remembered the Spanish Armada,

19:29.990 --> 19:32.730
Gravesend, Woolwich and Greenwich,

19:33.910 --> 19:36.590
places which I had heard of even in my country.

19:36.590 --> 19:40.890
At length we saw the numerous steeples of London,

19:41.550 --> 19:43.690
St. Paul's towering above them all,

19:44.110 --> 19:47.050
and the Tower famed in English history.

